## Description {#details}

<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sparsebitvector">SparseBitVector</a> is an implementation of a bitvector that is sparse by only storing the elements that have non-zero bits set.

In order to make this fast for the most common cases, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sparsebitvector">SparseBitVector</a> is implemented as a linked list of SparseBitVectorElements. We maintain a pointer to the last <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/sparsebitvectorelement">SparseBitVectorElement</a> accessed (in the form of a list iterator), in order to make multiple in-order test/set constant time after the first one is executed. Note that using vectors to store <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/sparsebitvectorelement">SparseBitVectorElement</a>&#39;s does not work out very well because it causes insertion in the middle to take enormous amounts of time with a large amount of bits. Other structures that have better worst cases for insertion in the middle (various balanced trees, etc) do not perform as well in practice as a linked list with this iterator kept up to date. They are also significantly more memory intensive.
